fc38b028-612b-4494-8cbd-3c390dd13ffb	4505f6e8-eb19-4c4f-a460-1ed6b8dcccab	0	Losing Your Voice	Hey, welcome to Radiohead Space, it's Dora. Today, we're taking a walk down memory lane, about five years ago. I had just gone through the breakup of a five-year relationship, the kind that wasn't dramatic or explosive just over. I'm sitting in my friend's kitchen and she's making me tea while I'm having what I can only describe as an identity crisis, because for the first time in years I had no idea what I wanted. My friend starts listing all the things I should do. You should travel, you should date, you should focus on your career, you should cut your hair, you should redecorate your apartment. My mom calls later with her own list, he should take time to heal, you should go to therapy, you should definitely not date anyone for at least a year. Then there's my coworker, you should get back out there immediately, you should download all the dating apps, you should show him what he's missing. And I'm sitting there with all this advice swirling around me like a tornado, and I realize I can't hear my own voice anymore. I don't know if I want to travel or stay put, date or be alone, cut my hair or grow it out. The noise had gotten so loud that I'd gone completely silent inside. And you know that feeling when you're trying to have a conversation and a crowded restaurant and there's so much background noise that you can't make out what the other person across from you is saying, that's what happens to our inner voice sometimes. Life gets so loud. From other people's opinions, social media messages, cultural expectations, our own racing thoughts that we lose the ability to hear ourselves. And here's the thing about losing your inner voice. It doesn't happen overnight, it's gradual. You start outsourcing small decisions, then bigger ones. You start asking everyone else what they think you should do instead of checking in with what feels right for you. Before you know it, you're living someone else's version of your own life, wondering why nothing feels quite right.	\N	13.12	138.256	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:28.636549+00	\N
7cecaeb1-7310-46de-ba54-b54b5c94cf37	4505f6e8-eb19-4c4f-a460-1ed6b8dcccab	1	Seeking External Answers	But here's what I learned during that messy post-breakup period. Your inner voice doesn't disappear, but just gets quiet. And with the right conditions, you can learn to hear it again. Now, after the breakup, I became an advice seeking machine. Should I keep our shared Netflix account? Should I stay in our old neighborhood? Should I tell people we broke up or wait until they noticed? I was treating my own life like a multiple choice test, and everyone else had the answer key. The turning point came when I was at this metaphysical bookstore, standing in this self-help section with my arms full of books that different people had recommended. This one will help you get over him. This one will help you find yourself. This one will help you never get hurt again. I'm standing there with this tower of other people's solutions to my problems, and the bookstore lady next to me says, girl, you look overwhelmed. I laughed and said, I'm just trying to figure out how to put my life back together. She smiled and said something I'll never forget. Well, what if you already know, and you just need to get quiet enough to hear it? She went on to share how sometimes we turn to external forms of guidance in these moments, but sometimes the best guidance comes from within.	\N	138.98	215.944	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:28.636549+00	\N
50a4629c-d2f6-40ca-a7f3-a4297a6bccd7	4505f6e8-eb19-4c4f-a460-1ed6b8dcccab	2	Choosing Silence	So that night I did something different. I turned my phone off, didn't ask anyone for advice, and just sat in my apartment and complete silence for the first time in months. Can you know what happened? After about 20 minutes of my mind racing with everyone else's voices, I started to hear something underneath all that noise. A tiny voice that said, I'm actually going to stay in this neighborhood because I love my coffee shop. Maybe changing our shared Netflix account isn't as big of a problem as I'm making it out to be. I'll tell people when I'm ready, not when they expect me to. Now, it wasn't dramatic wisdom, and it wasn't earth-shattering insights. It was just me, quiet, clear, and surprisingly sure about the small things.	\N	219.52	264.586	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:28.636549+00	\N
9f303dc5-1d26-4cb7-8d4e-431e40da6862	4505f6e8-eb19-4c4f-a460-1ed6b8dcccab	3	Reclaiming Your Voice	So here's what I learned about finding your voice again, and the world gets too loud, create actual quiet, not just less noise, but real silence. Turn off the phone, step away from the advice givers. And give your inner voice space to speak. Start with small questions. Don't ask yourself, what's my life purpose? Ask, do I want to hear coffee right now? Trust your answers to the small things, and your confidence and bigger decisions will grow. Notice whose voices live in your head. When you think I should, pause and ask, is this me talking, or is this my mom, friends, society, Instagram, practice the phrase, let me think about it. Instead of immediately asking for advice, try sitting with decisions for a bit. He might be surprised by what bubbles up. Remember that your inner voice might be different now. After big life changes, who you are might have shifted. The voice that emerges might surprise you.	\N	267.23	327.041	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:28.636549+00	\N
e2761120-1188-4ccb-b603-3e151889107f	4505f6e8-eb19-4c4f-a460-1ed6b8dcccab	4	Trusting Your Wisdom	The beautiful thing about reconnecting with inner voice is that it's always been there, waiting patiently under all the noise. It doesn't judge you for not listening for a while. It just quietly offers its wisdom, whenever you're ready to hear it. So if you're feeling lost in the noise right now, if everyone else's voices are drowning out your own, know that this is temporary. Your inner wisdom is still there. Maybe today you can just find five minutes of quiet. Maybe you can practice trusting yourself with one small decision. And maybe you can notice whose voice is actually speaking when you think about what you should do. Your voice matters, your inner knowing is valid. And you don't need anyone else's permission to trust what you hear when you get quiet enough to listen.	\N	327.165	377.112	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:28.636549+00	\N
fe458fad-dc86-4b87-862a-ad41feda1289	4505f6e8-eb19-4c4f-a460-1ed6b8dcccab	5	Looking Ahead	Now what I discovered next in my journey was fascinating. I finally started hearing myself again, but then I made the mistake of turning my healing into another project to master. I'll tell you about that tomorrow. Thanks so much for listening, and I'll see you for the next part of this story.	\N	377.266	395.209	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:28.636549+00	\N
0b4d6a13-5299-4bf6-968e-c371021ef96a	586c1526-3b29-4fc5-8b16-a887b41cbbb0	0	Power Of Humility	Hi there, Dora here, and welcome to Radiohead Space. So a few months ago, I found myself sitting in front of 12 eager faces in my teacher training program. I was in the middle of explaining this complex mindfulness concept, and one of my students raised her hand and said, actually Dora, I think you might have that backwards. My first instinct was that familiar heat of embarrassment rising up. You know that feeling, when your ego is exposed and wants to defend itself at all costs, but then I paused. I really looked at what she was pointing out and realized, she was absolutely right. I had gotten it completely backwards, and in that moment I had a choice. I could try to save face and double down on being wrong, or I could do something radical. I could delight in being wrong, and here's what I teach my mindfulness students, and what I had to learn myself that day. Humility isn't just nice to have as a teacher or practitioner, it's essential. Because the moment we think we know everything, the moment we're so attached to being right that we can't see where we're wrong, we stop being able to learn, we stop being able to grow, we stop being present to us actually happening right now.	\N	13.37	94.459	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:38.242566+00	\N
ae46e51a-00d3-4c79-a427-f1342b43c14a	586c1526-3b29-4fc5-8b16-a887b41cbbb0	1	Beginner's Mind	In Zen Buddhism there's this concept called beginner's mind, approaching everything with openness, eagerness, and freedom from preconceptions. Even when you're the expert, even when you're the teacher, and one of the most beautiful things about beginner's mind, it means you get to be wrong. It means I don't know, becomes an admirable position, not a shameful one. What if being wrong isn't a failure of intelligence, but a doorway to deeper understanding?	\N	94.61	123.077	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:38.242566+00	\N
cdff0669-3871-4dc9-a27d-d88c6fe935da	586c1526-3b29-4fc5-8b16-a887b41cbbb0	2	Admitting Not Knowing	So when I first started teaching mindfulness, I thought I had to have all the answers. I thought admitting I didn't know something would make me look incompetent or unqualified. So I'd prepare for classes like I was cramming for a final exam. I'd research every possible question someone might ask. I'd craft answers that sounded wise and authoritative. But the more I tried to be the all-knowing teacher, the more disconnected I became from the actual experience of mindfulness, which is about being present to not knowing, to uncertainty, to the mystery of each moment. A participant asked me about grief, specifically how to be mindful when you're in the middle of profound loss. I started giving my prepared response about acceptance and letting go, but something felt off. This person was in real pain, and my textbook answer felt hollow. So I stopped mid-sentence and said, you know what? I actually don't know. I've never lost a spouse like you have. I can only share what I've learned about being present with difficult emotions, but honestly, you might know more about navigating grief mindfully than I do. Would you be willing to share what you've discovered so far? And what happened next was so magical. This person shared insights about presence and pain that were more profound than anything I could have taught. The whole room leaned in and we were all learning together.	\N	125.97	210.24	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:38.242566+00	\N
f9779e1d-d5d3-4bbe-b69d-ed49fc8573aa	586c1526-3b29-4fc5-8b16-a887b41cbbb0	3	Teaching Uncertainty	This shifted my perspective about teaching. Now when I train new mindfulness teachers, the first thing I tell them is, you're willingness to be without knowing is your greatest strength. I teach them that I don't know, but let's explore this together. It's often a better response than trying to have all the answers. I show them how admitting when they're wrong model something beautiful to their students. That growth and learning never stop. That wisdom includes uncertainty. That being human means being imperfect.	\N	212.72	243.748	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:38.242566+00	\N
3c468ab0-033c-4c49-b2ce-51ec2e27998c	586c1526-3b29-4fc5-8b16-a887b41cbbb0	4	Reframing Being Wrong	So here's something I invite you to consider. What if being wrong wasn't something to avoid, but something to welcome? What if I don't know wasn't a sign of weakness, but a sign of wisdom? When we're wrong about something, it means we're learning. When we don't know something, it means we're still curious. When we admit our mistakes from modeling the kind of humility that allows real connection to happen. So, try this. The next time you catch yourself being wrong about something, big or small, instead of getting defensive or embarrassed, get curious. Ask yourself, what can I learn from this? What new understanding is trying to emerge? In practice saying these radical phrases like, I don't know, but I'd love to learn. I was wrong about that. Thank you for correcting me. I'm not sure. What do you think? These aren't admissions of failure. They're invitations to growth.	\N	247.49	300.807	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:38.242566+00	\N
6d943d8e-1ebc-4d46-bf72-1dc66e11d5e6	586c1526-3b29-4fc5-8b16-a887b41cbbb0	5	Hold Knowledge Lightly	My teacher training program, we have this saying, hold your knowledge lightly. Because the tighter we grip what we think we know, the less room we have for new understanding. The most profound teachers I know are the ones who say, I don't know, but the same competency say, I know. They understand that wisdom includes uncertainty, that expertise includes humility, that being right all the time is actually a barrier to real learning.	\N	301.81	328.567	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:38.242566+00	\N
7ec0ec15-fecd-4a52-ad77-17c6cc2bbea2	586c1526-3b29-4fc5-8b16-a887b41cbbb0	6	Embrace Not Knowing	So for today, see if you can find one small way to embrace not knowing. Maybe it's admitting when you don't understand something, instead of pretending you do. Maybe it's asking a genuine question instead of making an assumption. And maybe it's letting yourself be corrected by someone without your ego throwing a tantrum. Every time you're willing to be wrong, you create space to be more right than you were before. Every time you say, I don't know, you open a door to discovering something new. And every time you choose humility over being right, you choose growth over stagnation. The grace isn't in never being wrong. It's in how beautifully you can dance with being wrong when it happens. So I'll leave it here for today, friends. Thank you so much for stopping by and listening, and I'll see you tomorrow.	\N	332.26	380.256	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:38.242566+00	\N
a27f5708-63c9-4e8a-a2f7-d85470f54e85	1401a240-300e-462f-9c5c-a7c94827524f	0	Introduction	Hi, and welcome to Radiohead Space at Stora here. In honor and celebration of Pride Month, we are joined by two members of the Headspace team, Lindsey and Diana, for a heartfelt conversation about family identity and belonging. Together they share their experiences navigating life as LGBTQ plus women from coming out and finding community to building families of their own. At the heart of their story is something that we all share, the deep human need to be seen accepted and to know that we belong. That thread runs through all of us, whatever our experience may be. So along the way they reflect on the meaning of chosen family, the challenges and joys of parenthood, the importance of ally ship, and how compassionate connection can help us feel less alone. Whether you're a part of the LGBTQ plus community or supporting someone you love, we hope you enjoy this episode.	\N	14.18	78.234	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:51.762595+00	\N
71de720f-bb67-4184-8741-92a8b0a7935e	1401a240-300e-462f-9c5c-a7c94827524f	1	Origin Stories	Excited to have you here today, Lindsey and Diana, and yeah, maybe we can start with thinking about where you came from, maybe your origin story, and then the string that you've been on and how you would define family now. Sure, I can start. So growing up, my family is small, but taking it, my mom and my dad, while I was younger, they did divorce, but much family support on my mom's side with my grandparents. So that was a lot of my growing up. It was at my grandparents with my grandparents, my mom raised my sister and I kind of as a single mom. So defining family growing up was really just knowing that you had a loving environment, a safe environment, a loving home, and we had a lot of fun growing up. So that's really what family kind of look like for me then, and something that I strive for within my family. Now, as far as different, well, when I came out, I knew that my family dynamic was probably going to be different and may look like from when I grew up with, but yeah, that's that's a little bit about my background. Yeah, thank you for sharing with me about you, Diana. So my family is a little bit different. I was born into a split family, so my mom is a full Mexican born and raised in Mexico, and my dad is Egyptian born and raised in Egypt, and so both of them came from strong backgrounds, not only culturally, but also religiously, my mom and dad got divorced shortly after I was born, and then they both remarried and had additional kids. So I ended up having six siblings, three brothers, three sisters, a big mixture of all the things. But for me, family was always this different. It was always different from, I think a few of my friends that I had growing up, because I had two houses, you know, when I was with my mom, I was growing up Christian, which was my main house, and then when I went to visit my dad, I was practicing and doing all the most things, and so I really grew up in this different world, I think. There was always lots of love around, but I will say that, you know, I didn't really know what being gay meant when I was younger. I vividly do remember having a crush on this girl, asking part of my house with me, and I asked her to kiss me, and I remember telling her, she was like, no, and I remember saying, but our mom's in dad's kiss, like, so should we, you know, like, that's what you do when you play and so we got caught and I got in trouble. And I think it was in that moment that I kind of knew that I was different from my mom and my dad and the lives that they had built, and then you know, I later came out, you know, and I was thinking my late teens, and then obviously I got married to a woman. So now I know what it is to build my own family and to be in a different space and what I grew up in.	\N	78.526	254.005	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:51.762595+00	\N
2ad3e256-5475-4aa0-a7dc-eee50bf497e9	5c511d15-cbdf-46b5-a91d-1fb44ab72581	0	Introduction	Hey everybody, welcome back for another episode of the 5-minute Disoppoship podcast. My name is Lauren Hicks, and on this podcast I share 5-minute episodes to help you grow in your faith. This podcast is about discipleship and spiritual growth. It's my prayer that these short episodes inspire you and encourage you to be a fully devoted follower of Jesus Christ. So if you're new to the podcast, let me invite you to subscribe on your favorite podcast app so that you can join us each day.	\N	4.72	36.519	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:29:05.58386+00	\N
cb99e67e-b660-417a-a229-06ba4f5ed69b	1401a240-300e-462f-9c5c-a7c94827524f	2	Chosen Family	Yeah, yeah, thank you both so much for sharing your story and maybe we can talk about this concept of being different and I know for myself and some of the journeys that I've been on, it can be isolating, right, to be different, to be kind of building the path as you're walking forward. So I'm curious for both of you, where did you find support? Who was your support system? Was it your actual family or, you know, there's this idea of chosen family as well? But who was keeping you grounded as you were kind of learning more about yourself and this new and different path that you were on? Yeah, that's a great question. In the time when I did realize I was gay, it's because I had in high school friends that were identifying as gay and coming out and I didn't really know what that meant to because I didn't have exposure to that within my family or within my friends up until that point. And so I would say that was significantly a support system for me, was my friend group that identified similarly to me yet I didn't know what that meant truly and what that was going to mean for my family either because when I did come out they weren't very accepting at first. And so that was difficult and I did feel isolated from my family because I felt like it couldn't talk about it. I felt like it couldn't bring, you know, crushes or I was dating around and they didn't understand it. I'm at the time they just thought it was a phase and maybe perhaps if I did go talk to the pastor at the church like that would change things because we did grow up slightly religious and at a point I think they just still very much loved me and cared for me but they didn't know how to navigate it with me. And so they just kind of put it to the side if you will and I didn't feel like I could be embedded in my family quite as much anymore at least being open and honest about what I was going through at that time of coming out and who I was hanging out with and what I was exploring which to be honest was okay because I think at that age not very many teenagers, you know, really want to do that with our parents or grandparents or even my sister too was not as open to it as she is now to who I married with and in my family but I would say for sure it was very important that my friend group that understood me and that they were also navigating a similar path we all had each other so that really became my family was my friend group and feeling safe and supported by them. Yeah I think very similar I think also isolation for me has come in waves when I first came out I was very open, loud and proud. I was so excited to just say it out loud and to tell everyone and of course I had high school boyfriend so it was weird to tell people who were like oh wait what about you know XYZ guy and I'm like you didn't matter you know and so it's like that I think was like one specific type of phase and then I think as I got older and I started really dating and figuring out who I was and who I wanted to be with I think it came in waves of sort of like even where I was in my physically and emotionally because I moved around a lot as an adult I lived abroad and then I came back to the States and so as I was channeling those waves of isolation of being physically isolated you know I also found solace with my friends who were around me and they truly did become my chosen family where I felt so supported.	\N	254.13	463.968	440a8cad-2a53-4169-b1cd-08117e1fad58	2026-06-17 15:28:51.762595+00	\N
d99f94cd-98e0-4f64-9b4d-0462f2ae8185	1401a240-300e-462f-9c5c-a7c94827524f	3	Building Families	Yeah yeah thank you for naming that and maybe we can talk about even the present moment now and we think about what it takes to build a family I think a lot of people within the LGBTQ plus community take different paths right whether it's through adoption or fertility treatment, serigacy, co-parenting, whatever it may be and so I'm curious for you all now in this present day what does that journey of building family look like for you and if you feel open to share like some of the unexpected challenges that you've had to whether external or even internal right because sometimes that those challenges can come from our own beliefs and thoughts about how this should be going or how it's supposed to go so maybe we'll start with UNC. Yeah absolutely so I knew from a very young age even before I'm that my wife that I wanted kids that was not negotiable I was going to figure out a way to make it happen and so that was literally one of the first questions I asked when I met my wife when I was at a point where I knew that I needed to make a decision on what my journey was going to look like for having kids on our first date I said are you open having kids and she said you know I've never thought about it from a standpoint of like if I was going to carry kids or whether or not I have kids in whatever my future held with a partner but yes I'm open to it and so that opened the door a little bit wider so where our path would lead to but I knew I always wanted to have kids so what that was alongside somebody in the journey or by myself so I understood at a certain point in my 20s that it could make it happen from a fertility perspective knowing that I was gay and and so for myself and my wife and I got married and decided to have kids our fertility journey started with just kind of asking questions from our friends who had been on those journeys and understanding what they did to learn more about the process we ultimately navigated in researching and understanding from sperm clinics what we would to go through to choose a donor and follow the process from there and selecting a fertility clinic since ultimately I knew very much that I wanted to carry a child and get birth we decided to start with me first and the process was scary and to be honest not in where we we were living out at the time lost in Texas like it was pretty easy to be honest but we we went with a fertility clinic that was working with couples that we knew and and referred us and you know they they went through the normal processes for understanding what our family history was and kind of current state at our age for getting present and we started out with just IUI and we're fortunate to for myself to get pregnant on the first try which was very shocking and surprising and and we weren't expecting that we were expecting a little bit of a longer journey and perhaps some additional testing or additional stuff just based on what we'd heard from other people but yeah it happened very quickly for us which was a blessing but also very surprising and the rest of our journey didn't quite go the same so so we ultimately had to navigate that and and some you know ups and downs and strong emotions through that my wife tried to get pregnant as well and it was unsuccessful we both tried to get pregnant for our second memory unsuccessful each of us and we had to stop and kind of pause and decide what would happen if we weren't able to have a second child what were our thoughts there we even talked about adoption and things like that but as it turned out after a couple of rounds of IUI and some additional you know treatments and things like that I was able to get pregnant with our second child as well so yeah that was kind of our journey from never one to number two so for me it was actually very much the opposite I didn't think I wanted kids for a very very long time I think for me I was more I w